Orchestrates the full set of wrapped tool checks (fmt, clippy, tests, contracts, architecture, etc., defined in `specs.rs`/`SPECS`) into one `Report`, via an injected `Runner` abstraction (so callers can substitute a fake runner in tests).

Key mechanics: `fmt` is special-cased upstream (per module doc) as the only check allowed to mutate mechanically and unconditionally; here, the more general self-healing behavior is in `run_spec`: if `contracts` or `architecture` fails, `specs::regen_command(spec.name)` is invoked once (the generator's `--write` mode) and the check is re-run once — the *recheck's* outcome is what's reported, not the original failure, unless the regen command itself fails to execute, in which case the original outcome is kept. This is a single attempt, not a retry loop.

`run_spec` distinguishes three outcomes carefully: `CheckReport::skipped` (tool binary missing — `CheckError::ToolMissing`), `CheckReport::errored` (spawn/exec failure, e.g. infra issue), and a normal parsed report. A failing check whose parser (`spec.parser`) yields zero diagnostics gets a synthesized one via `failure_hint`, which pulls the last non-empty trimmed line from stderr then stdout — so a failing check is never silently empty.

`effective_args` injects `-p <package>` right after the subcommand (position `1..1`) only for `spec.tool == "cargo"`; non-cargo checks ignore `package` entirely.

Entry point: `pub fn run_selected<R: Runner>(runner: &R, max: usize, only: Option<&[String]>, package: Option<&str>) -> Report` — iterates `SPECS`, filters by `only` via `wanted`, runs each into a `BTreeMap<String, CheckReport>`. Diagnostics per check are capped at `max` via `CheckReport::build`.

Depends on `specs` submodule for the check table and regen command mapping — adding a new check means editing `specs.rs`, not this file.